-- Russian Stocks Rebound on Positive U.S. Business Activity Data
-- B y   D e n i s   M a t e r n o v s k y
-- 2011-12-29T17:18:34Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-29/russian-stocks-retreat-for-third-day-as-oil-drops-ruble-weakens.html
Russia ’s stock index gained today,
after declining in the previous two days, on data that U.S.
business activity and home sales exceeded forecast.  The Micex Index increased 0.3 percent to 1,387.06 by the
end of trading in Moscow. The dollar-measured  RTS Index (RTSI$)  slid 1.2
percent to 1,365.13 for a yearly drop of 23 percent.  Index of pending U.S. home sales rose more than economists
forecast, sending stocks in the U.S. and  Europe  higher. Earlier
in the day, Micex fell as much 1.6 percent and 20 of its 30
stocks retreated as oil, the country’s biggest export, traded
near the lowest price in a week. Crude oil for February delivery
fell 73 cents, or 0.7 percent, to $98.63 at 11:05 a.m. on the
 New York Mercantile Exchange . The ruble depreciated 1.6 percent
to 32.2395 against the dollar, weakening for a third day.  OAO Gazprom (GAZP) , a gas export monopoly, gained 0.4 percent to
170.50 rubles after having fallen near its weakest closing level
since Dec. 19.  OAO GMK Norilsk Nickel (GMKN) , Russia’s largest miner,
rose 2.9 percent to 4,925 rubles, erasing an earlier drop of as
much as 1.5 percent, after the company said on its website it
plans to increase  capital spending  by at least 7 percent and
will exceed $3 billion in 2012.  OAO Rushydro (HYDR) , Russia’s largest hydropower producer, was
among the worst performers as it slid 3.9 percent to 95.51
kopeks, the lowest since May 5 2009.  Federal Grid Co. (FEES) , the
state-run power-line operator, fell 2.3 percent to 27.7 kopeks.
 VTB Group (VTBR) , Russia’s second-biggest lender, declined 2.2 percent
to 5.79 kopeks and  OAO Sberbank (SBER) , the country’s biggest lender,
slipped 0.5 percent to 78.90 rubles, heading for its lowest
close since Nov. 25.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Denis Maternovsky in Moscow at 
